<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-pop_sd_estimation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Estimating the population standard deviation</title>
    <p>
        In the previous section, we used the sample mean to estimate the population mean. 
        We can apply the same principle to variability. Although the standard deviation of a sample can be calculated directly from 
        the data, the true population standard deviation is usually unknown. 
        Therefore, we use the sample standard deviation to estimate the population standard deviation.
    </p>
    <p>
        Unlike the sample mean, however, the sample standard deviation tends to slightly underestimate the true population standard 
        deviation, particularly when the sample size is small. This systematic difference is known as <em>bias</em>. To reduce this bias, 
        statistical software applies a small correction by dividing by <m>N-1</m> instead of <m>N</m> when calculating the variance. 
        This adjustment, known as <em>Bessel's correction</em>, provides a better estimate of the population variance and, consequently, 
        the population standard deviation.
    </p>
    <p>
        Continuing with the <c>effort</c> dataset introduced in the previous section, 
        we can estimate the population standard deviation for the <c>hours</c> and <c>grade</c> variables using the <c>One Variable Summarise</c> dialog. 
        Open the dialog through <c>Describe &gt; One Variable &gt; Summarise...</c>. 
        Select the <c>Customised</c> tab, move the <c>hours</c> and <c>grade</c> variables into the <c>Variable(s) to Summarise</c> box, 
        ensure the required summary statistics are selected, and click <c>OK</c>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-estimate-sd-dialog">
        <caption>
            The <c>One Variable Summarise</c> dialog used to obtain summary statistics for the <c>hours</c> and <c>grade</c> 
            variables in the <c>effort</c> dataset using the <c>Customised</c> tab.
        </caption>
        <image source="images\estimation\estimate_sd_dialog.png"/>
    </figure>

    <figure xml:id="fig-estimate-sd-output">
        <caption>
            Summary output showing the mean and standard deviation for the <c>hours</c> and <c>grade</c> variables in the <c>effort</c> dataset.
        </caption>
        <image source="images\estimation\estimate_sd_output.png"/>
    </figure>

    <p>
        The customised summary output reports several descriptive statistics, including the sample size, mean, 
        median and standard deviation for each variable. In this example, 
        the <c>hours</c> variable has a mean of 36.80 hours and a standard deviation of 25.52, while the <c>grade</c> variable has a 
        mean of 59.60 and a standard deviation of 32.52. The standard deviation measures how much the observations vary around the mean. 
        Larger values indicate greater variability, whereas smaller values indicate that the observations are more closely clustered 
        around the mean.
    </p>
    <p>
        R-Instat calculates the standard deviation using the <m>N-1</m> correction (Bessel's correction). 
        This is the standard deviation commonly reported in statistical analyses and provides the best available estimate of the population 
        standard deviation based on the sample data.
    </p>
    <p>
        If the sample observations are denoted by <m>X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_N</m>, 
        then the estimated population standard deviation is calculated as
        <md>
            \hat{\sigma}=
            \sqrt{\frac{1}{N-1}\sum_{i=1}^{N}(X_i-\bar{X})^2}
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        The corresponding estimate of the population variance is
        <md>
            \hat{\sigma}^{2}=
            \frac{1}{N-1}\sum_{i=1}^{N}(X_i-\bar{X})^2
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        Using <m>N-1</m> instead of <m>N</m> compensates for the tendency of small samples to underestimate the true population variability. 
        As the sample size increases, the difference between dividing by <m>N</m> and <m>N-1</m> becomes negligible.
    </p>
    <p>
        To distinguish between quantities calculated from the sample and the corresponding population parameters, 
        the notation shown in <xref ref="table-estimation-sd-notation"/> is used throughout this book.
    </p>

    <table xml:id="table-estimation-sd-notation">
        <title>Notation for standard deviation and variance</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                <cell halign="left">Symbol</cell>
                <cell>Meaning</cell>
                <cell>Known?</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell halign="left"><m>s</m></cell>
                <cell>Sample standard deviation</cell>
                <cell>Yes, calculated from the sample data</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell halign="left"><m>\sigma</m></cell>
                <cell>Population standard deviation</cell>
                <cell>Usually unknown</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell halign="left"><m>\hat{\sigma}</m></cell>
                <cell>Estimate of the population standard deviation</cell>
                <cell>Yes, obtained from the sample</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell halign="left"><m>s^2</m></cell>
                <cell>Sample variance</cell>
                <cell>Yes, calculated from the sample data</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell halign="left"><m>\sigma^2</m></cell>
                <cell>Population variance</cell>
                <cell>Usually unknown</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell halign="left"><m>\hat{\sigma}^2</m></cell>
                <cell>Estimate of the population variance</cell>
                <cell>Yes, obtained from the sample</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </table>    
</subsection>